Suppose that K\subset M is obtained from a compact lift \widetilde{K}\subset\mathbb{H}^{d} by projection \mathbb{H}^{d}\to\mathbb{H}^{d}/\Gamma. One can pick such \widetilde{K} in the Dirichlet fundamental polyhedron D\_{\Gamma}(o) for some point o\in\mathbb{H}^{d}. Then there is R>0 such that \widetilde{K}\subset B\_{\mathbb{H}^{d}}(o,R). Theorem 2.8 implies that there exist (K\_{n},r\_{n})–approximate isometries f\_{n}:(M\_{n},v\_{n})\to(M,v) with K\_{n}\to 1 and r\_{n}\to\infty as n\to\infty. This means that there is N>0 such that for any n>N we have r\_{n}>R and a diffeomorphism of domains in M\_{n} and M, where the selected domain in M covers the ball B\_{M}(x,r\_{n}).
